	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>kevtris</b> [ Sun Nov 13, 2005 1:33 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Great Hierophant wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So I would have to solder eight resistors, or one resistor pack on the converter between the male and female connectors.  As I have a Famicom, I don't really have much of a use for my Famicom to NES converter.  (I like to use it with Famicom games with internal sound chips in them to demonstrate what happens when the sound chip can't receive/send the sound from/to the cart.)  Would this ruin the converter for uses other than dumping cartridges?</div>
<br />
<br />Nope, the converter still works fine for all carts.  I always use my adultered converter when playing and dumping games.  What I did was pretty simple- I just lifted the pins of the fami connector up off the PCB with an x-acto knife as I heated the solder up.  then I got 8 560 ohm 1/4W 5% resistors and soldered them from the pins of the connector to the pads on the board.  I think I snipped them off a board.  The leads were super short but this was fine and was desireable for this job.  It's worked great for every single cart I've thrown at it.
<br />
<br />A couple times, some Sachen carts in the usual NES form factor were screwing up and crashing CopyNES (no licensed or 3rd party carts had ever done that) so I simply plugged my NES to fami converter into the adultered fami to NES converter and all was well <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":-)" title="Smile" />  Even though the cart was sticking way out why I was done, it worked.  I've chained no less than 3 converters before when I had the FDS RAM pack plugged in and that worked fine also.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


